shed feedback (13:15).\n\n- **Guille Santana** presented homepage mockups and marketing collateral, proposing to share markup links for collaborative comments.\n    - Christina noted she has a hard stop at **11:30 AM** and suggested that in-depth website feedback might require additional meetings or offline review.\n    - Jane supported this by confirming that the **11:30 AM** meeting was dedicated to brand and art direction, making this initial session suitable for high-level updates only.\n    - Christina proposed sending website drafts ahead of meetings (ideally by the prior Friday noon) to allow pre-review by herself, Jane, and Victor for more focused discussions.\n\n- The group agreed to maintain a centralized library of drafts and versions for easy reference and progress tracking, aiding internal communication and leadership updates.\n    - Christina pointed out that previous feedback loops lacked accessible shared files, which limited visibility and slowed approvals.\n    - Guille committed to sending all materials in a single email and later compiling them into one Markup file for easier access.\n\n## **Marketing Collateral and Vendor Decisions**\n\nThe team progressed on printed marketing materials with specific vendor and format choices to optimize quality and flexibility (18:12).\n\n- Guille shared research recommending **SmartPress** for printing **6x9 postcards**, citing better space utilization and quality compared to other vendors.\n    - Christina deferred vendor choice to the design experts, prioritizing print quality based on positive past experiences.\n    - She requested copy layout revisions, specifically to better utilize front space with a clear callout (\"Now open in your neighborhood\") and more engaging back design using texture or color variation to avoid a bland look.\n    - Christina also noted that campaign operational readiness depends on sign-off from the new operations hire confirming reporting and management steps.\n\n## **Brand Color Alignment and Design Consistency**\n\nThe team agreed to standardize on the **royal blue** color from existing brand guidelines to avoid confusion and maintain consistency across digital and print assets (21:50).\n\n- **Jane** provided detailed brand context, explaining the use of **royal blue** and a very dark blue in different bank contexts, noting the shift away from lighter blues and teals due to poor reproduction and brand clarity.\n    - Jane and Christina both emphasized that the royal blue is bright, corporate, and visually distinct, making it the preferred choice for headlines and callouts.\n    - Christina explained that despite previous brand guidelines, some on-the-fly design adjustments are expected as real projects expose new needs.\n    - Jane sent the official color codes (CMYK, PMS, Hex) via email to ensure all designers have exact references.\n    - Guille confirmed the design team is currently updating all materials to align with the royal blue and correct fonts, including the newsletter template and website assets.\n\n- The group agreed to test color combinations across collateral to balance yellows, royal blue, and teal without diluting brand identity.\n    - Jane stressed the importance of readability, especially for disclaimers and legal text, which must not overpower the main messaging.\n    - Colin and Guille committed to creating color variations for review rather than exploring new palettes, focusing on refining existing brand colors.\n\n## **Project Communication and Documentation Practices**\n\nImproving communication protocols and document sharing was prioritized to support efficient reviews and stakeholder engagement (16:29).\n\n- Christina requested that draft materials be sent in advance of meetings to allow proper review and preparation, helping meetings be more productive and reducing last-minute changes.\n- Jane highlighted the importance of receiving PDFs and high-quality images rather than relying only on markup links or scre